{"title_page": "Wrestling World 1999", "text_new": "{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name=Wrestling World 1999\n|image=File:Naoya-Ogawa20111218.jpg\n|caption=[[Naoya Ogawa]], who wrestled [[Shinya Hashimoto]] to a no contest at the event.\n|promotion=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]\n|date={{dts|1999|1|4}}<ref name=Jan4-99>{{cite web | url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/newjapan/tokyodome.html#99 | title= Wrestling World 1999 | date= January 4, 1999 | accessdate= April 13, 2010 | publisher= ProWrestlingHistory.com}}</ref>\n|venue=[[Tokyo Dome]]\n|city=[[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n|attendance=52,500<ref name=Jan4-99/>\n|liveevent=N\n|event= [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]]\n|lastevent2=[[Final Power Hall in Tokyo Dome]]\n|nextevent2=[[Wrestling World 2000|Wrestling World]]\n}}\n'''Wrestling World 1999''' was a [[professional wrestling]] event produced by [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW). It took place on January 4, 1998 in the [[Tokyo Dome]]. Wrestling World 1999 was the eighth [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]] held by NJPW. The show drew 52,500 spectators and $5,300,000 in ticket sales.<ref name=Jan4-99/> The show featured 10 matches in total including four championship matches, three of which saw the championship change hands.\n\n==Production==\n===Background===\nThe [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]] is NJPW's biggest [[List of NJPW pay-per-view events|annual event]] and has been called \"the largest professional wrestling show in the world outside of the United States\" and the \"Japanese equivalent to the [[Super Bowl]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.prowrestling.net/article.php?40241 | title = GFW News: New Japan Pro Wrestling \"Wrestle Kingdom 9\" press conference details | date=December 23, 2014 | accessdate=October 9, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net}}</ref><ref name=WK11AXSPWT>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/12/13/new-japans-wrestlekingdom-11-air-axs-tv-starting-jan-13-four-weekly-special-episodes-ross-barnett-commentary/ | title = New Japan's WrestleKingdom 11 to air on AXS TV starting Jan. 13 in four weekly special episodes with Ross & Barnett on commentary | last=Keller | first=Wade | authorlink=Wade Keller | date=December 13, 2016 | accessdate=October 9, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> \n\n===Storylines===\nWrestling World 1999 featured [[Professional wrestling match types|professional wrestling matches]] that involved different wrestlers from pre-existing scripted feuds and [[Narrative thread|storylines]]. Wrestlers portrayed [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villains]], [[Face (professional wrestling)|heroes]], or [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#tweener|less distinguishable characters]] in scripted events that built tension and culminated in a wrestling match or series of matches.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/pro-wrestling.htm | title = How Pro Wrestling Works | last=Grabianowski | first=Ed | accessdate=October 9, 2017 | work=HowStuffWorks, Inc. | publisher=[[Discovery Communications]]}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|results=\n|times=<ref name=Jan4-99/>\n|match1=[[Manabu Nakanishi]] defeated [[Kazuyuki Fujita]]\n|stip1=[[Professional wrestling match types#Variations of singles matches|Singles match]]\n|time1=11:10\n|match2=[[Osamu Kido]], [[Tadao Yasuda]] and [[Tatsumi Fujinami]] defeated [[Kengo Kimura]], [[Michiyoshi Ohara]] and [[Tatsutoshi Goto]]\n|stip2=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Multiple man teamed matches|Six-man tag team match]]\n|time2=09:17\n|match3=[[Dr. Wagner, Jr.]] and [[Kendo Kashin]] defeated [[Shinjiro Otani]] and [[Tatsuhito Takaiwa]] (c)\n|stip3=[[Tag team]] match for the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Tag Team Championship]]\n|time3=16:53\n|match4=[[Jushin Thunder Liger]] (c) defeated [[Koji Kanemoto]]\n|stip4=Singles match for the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Championship]]\n|time4=23:11\n|match5=[[Kensuke Sasaki]] defeated [[Atsushi Onita]] by disqualification\n|stip5=Singles match\n|time5=05:55\n|match6=[[Yuji Nagata]] defeated [[Dave Beneteau|David Beneteau]]\n|stip6=Singles match\n|time6=05:30\n|match7=[[Don Frye]] defeated [[Brian Johnston (fighter)|Brian Johnston]] via referee stoppage\n|stip7=Singles match\n|time7=07:55\n|match8=[[Shinya Hashimoto]] wrestled [[Naoya Ogawa]] to a no contest\n|stip8=Singles match\n|time8=06:58\n|match9=[[Tencozy]] ([[Hiroyoshi Tenzan]] and [[Satoshi Kojima]]) defeated [[Genichiro Tenryu]] and [[Shiro Koshinaka]] (c)\n|stip9=Tag team match for the [[IWGP Tag Team Championship]]\n|time9=16:35\n|match10=[[Keiji Mutoh]] defeated [[Scott Norton]] (c)\n|stip10=Singles match for the [[IWGP Heavyweight Championship]]\n|time10=19:01\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.njpw.co.jp/ NJPW.co.jp] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{New Japan Pro Wrestling events|January 4 Tokyo Dome Show}}\n\n[[Category:1999 in professional wrestling]]\n[[Category:1999 in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:January 1999 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:January 4 Tokyo Dome Show|1999]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name=Wrestling World 1999\n|image=File:Naoya-Ogawa20111218.jpg\n|caption=[[Naoya Ogawa]], who wrestled [[Shinya Hashimoto]] to a no contest at the event.\n|promotion=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]\n|date={{dts|1999|1|4}}<ref name=Jan4-99>{{cite web | url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/newjapan/tokyodome.html#99 | title= Wrestling World 1999 | date= January 4, 1999 | accessdate= April 13, 2010 | publisher= ProWrestlingHistory.com}}</ref>\n|venue=[[Tokyo Dome]]\n|city=[[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n|attendance=52,500<ref name=Jan4-99/>\n|liveevent=N\n|event= [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]]\n|lastevent2=[[Final Power Hall in Tokyo Dome]]\n|nextevent2=[[Wrestling World 2000|Wrestling World]]\n}}\n'''Wrestling World 1999''' was a [[professional wrestling]] event produced by [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW). It took place on January 4, 1998 in the [[Tokyo Dome]]. Wrestling World 1999 was the eighth [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]] held by NJPW. The show drew 52,500 spectators and $5,300,000 in ticket sales.<ref name=Jan4-99/> The show featured 10 matches in total including four championship matches, three of which saw the championship change hands.\n\n==Production==\n===Background===\nThe [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]] is NJPW's biggest [[List of NJPW pay-per-view events|annual event]] and has been called \"the largest professional wrestling show in the world outside of the United States\" and the \"Japanese equivalent to the [[Super Bowl]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.prowrestling.net/article.php?40241 | title = GFW News: New Japan Pro Wrestling \"Wrestle Kingdom 9\" press conference details | date=December 23, 2014 | accessdate=October 9, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net}}</ref><ref name=WK11AXSPWT>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/12/13/new-japans-wrestlekingdom-11-air-axs-tv-starting-jan-13-four-weekly-special-episodes-ross-barnett-commentary/ | title = New Japan's WrestleKingdom 11 to air on AXS TV starting Jan. 13 in four weekly special episodes with Ross & Barnett on commentary | last=Keller | first=Wade | authorlink=Wade Keller | date=December 13, 2016 | accessdate=October 9, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> \n\n===Storylines===\nWrestling World 1999 featured [[Professional wrestling match types|professional wrestling matches]] that involved different wrestlers from pre-existing scripted feuds and [[Narrative thread|storylines]]. Wrestlers portrayed [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villains]], [[Face (professional wrestling)|heroes]], or [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#tweener|less distinguishable characters]] in scripted events that built tension and culminated in a wrestling match or series of matches.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/pro-wrestling.htm | title = How Pro Wrestling Works | last=Grabianowski | first=Ed | accessdate=October 9, 2017 | work=HowStuffWorks, Inc. | publisher=[[Discovery Communications]]}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|results=\n|times=<ref name=Jan4-99/>\n|match1=[[Manabu Nakanishi]] defeated [[Kazuyuki Fujita]]\n|stip1=[[Professional wrestling match types#Variations of singles matches|Singles match]]\n|time1=11:10\n|match2=[[Osamu Kido]], [[Tadao Yasuda]] and [[Tatsumi Fujinami]] defeated [[Kengo Kimura]], [[Michiyoshi Ohara]] and [[Tatsutoshi Goto]]\n|stip2=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Multiple man teamed matches|Six-man tag team match]]\n|time2=09:17\n|match3=[[Dr. Wagner, Jr.]] and [[Kendo Kashin]] defeated [[Shinjiro Otani]] and [[Tatsuhito Takaiwa]] (c)\n|stip3=[[Tag team]] match for the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Tag Team Championship]]\n|time3=16:53\n|match4=[[Jushin Thunder Liger]] (c) defeated [[Koji Kanemoto]]\n|stip4=Singles match for the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Championship]]\n|time4=23:11\n|match5=[[Kensuke Sasaki]] defeated [[Atsushi Onita]] by disqualification\n|stip5=Singles match\n|time5=05:55\n|match6=[[Yuji Nagata]] defeated [[Dave Beneteau|David Beneteau]]\n|stip6=Singles match\n|time6=05:30\n|match7=[[Don Frye]] defeated [[Brian Johnston (fighter)|Brian Johnston]] via referee stoppage\n|stip7=Singles match\n|time7=07:55\n|match8=[[Shinya Hashimoto]] wrestled [[Naoya Ogawa]] to a no contest\n|stip8=Singles match\n|time8=06:58\n|match9=[[Tencozy]] ([[Hiroyoshi Tenzan]] and [[Satoshi Kojima]]) defeated [[Genichiro Tenryu]] and [[Shiro Koshinaka]] (c)\n|stip9=Tag team match for the [[IWGP Tag Team Championship]]\n|time9=16:35\n|match10=[[Keiji Mutoh]] defeated [[Scott Norton]] (c)\n|stip10=Singles match for the [[IWGP Heavyweight Championship]]\n|time10=19:01\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.njpw.co.jp/ NJPW.co.jp] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{New Japan Pro Wrestling events|January 4 Tokyo Dome Show}}\n\n[[Category:1999 in professional wrestling]]\n[[Category:1999 in Japan]]\n[[Category:January 1999 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:January 4 Tokyo Do